In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrators composed of Islamic students took over the American Embassy in Tehran and detained 52 diplomats in hostages.
They had to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, and it could not, in fact, abandon Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had resulted from the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, later compounded by the failure of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States sparks a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iran feeling.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by the actor and performer Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a small victory in America.
Just before she's occupied, six employees leave the embassy.
