Szabo: "Germans have to play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the request of the Palestinians to obtain observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose the abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, however, without being overly critical of Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also opted for abstention during the vote on the establishment of an air-exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposes this measure.
Is Germany experiencing difficulties in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to withdraw from a policy so as to say as defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
Thus, the Germans meet on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still trying to find this role, but they're on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or Great Britain
What exactly does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt independent positions of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests affect Germany's position towards the conflict in the Middle East and the withdrawal of the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important openings in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to give public opinion, but also to the elites of the Arab countries.
There is no doubt that this is a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not just a unilateral relationship.
But this is a determining element in the German strategic reflections.
Does Germany interfere with its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I believe that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, views on the Palestinian initiative are different.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly demonstrates a great understanding of the European position.
But given the country's political configuration, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I think that the real differences of opinion are not so big that they always seem to be.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from being enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policy.
Is Germany experiencing difficulties in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think that makes things any easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not the case.
They cannot therefore join a wider political line and must affirm their unique position.
That is what they are currently doing in the euro area.
In my view, Germany will play a role as a locomotive in the future and will encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been sensitive.
But I think the Germans are well aware that they have to play a role that is more marked by their independence.
Does Germany play a role as a player in the international scene, does Germany just want to play a key role?
Or does it still have difficulties in taking on the leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still experiencing difficulties in playing a more important role.
Looking at, for example, the euro crisis, we note that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, this is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed with very diverse neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the U.S. influence on European policy only diminishes, but at the moment, the EU does not fill this gap, while who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're just less appreciated, that's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Washington Transatlantic Academy, where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America analyse together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Mark Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are famous brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trade mark officially deposited in China, but it has nothing to do with the original company.
The brand thus enjoys protection such as the company that bears its name cannot complain.
And even if she could, it's not certain she'd get a cause.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China," explains Thomas Pattloch, attorney at Taylor Wessing's office specializing in the violation of property law in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives at my office.
The simulators only need a few additional letters to be able to record their marks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, Lu-Gucci is recorded, and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is recorded.
German companies are also legally copying the sports goods manufacturer, such as Puma.
