For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the paved stone paths.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn their lives by wearing the sulfur of the Kawah Ijen volcano to the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulphuric gas from the earth's cracks is solidified by air contact.
After harvesting large sulphur rocks, which weigh nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the sharp paths.
There is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which peaks at 2,386 meters high, but the worn-out carriers spend more than 40 minutes to record this distance, at a pitch of tortoise, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a fake could cost them their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who fell dead in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The Kawah Ijen minors earn 5 cents of euros for each kilo of extracted sulphur.
