A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible slaughter there: the end of the "great countdown" of the Mayan calendar, December 21, to which many refer, as proof of the end of the coming world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was expected of him during the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax break that some have named "Armageddon of Debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists of the end of time thought that the apocalypse would start.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé to his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were talking about it, it was a very good time.
And remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to give courses on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last of history.
In Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker provides the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios leads to a certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons were to fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," said Vacker.
On the main campus of the University of State of Pennsylvania, the professor of History of Latin America Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of History of Art and Anthropology, made a team to give a course, simply called "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, if the world would not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the State of Pennsylvania, the final review will be carried out on the watch of the Apocalypse, which does not leave students any choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," said Restall.
The courses were fairly popular.
"It was completed in two hours," Restall said about its high-level student course, consisting of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, on the part of people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"This fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgeid Robinson, a 23-year-old religious and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, University of Rutgers-Camden.
Because the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
